# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scot
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scot/ac] The **.ac** top-level domain is the Internet country code (ccTLD) for Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha, used primarily for Ascension Island (Saint Helena has its own ccTLD, .sh).
[src:scot/ac] It is administered by NIC.AC, a subsidiary of the Afilias-owned company Internet Computer Bureau.
[src:scot/ac] Registration for the domain is open to anyone.
[src:scot/ac] The registry accepts registrations of internationalised domain names.
[src:scot/aero] Two-letter codes under `.aero` are reserved for airlines according to the IATA Airline Designators.
[src:scot/aero] While three-letter codes were initially reserved for airports (IATA airport code), they were released for registration by the larger aviation and aerospace community on December 1, 2008.
[src:scot/aero] The `aero` top-level domain was initially approved in 2001 for a 5-year term expiring December 17, 2006 as part of a proof-of-concept of new top-level domains.
[src:scot/aero] The agreement was extended in October 2006 for a six-month term until June 17, 2007, and continued to be renewed on a June–December six-month cycle through June 17, 2009.
[src:scot/aero] In 2009, SITA and ICANN completed a new 10-year sponsorship agreement for the operation of `.aero`.
[src:scot/africa] The .africa domain became available to the general public on 4 July 2017.
[src:scot/africa] .africa was launched at the African Union Commission in 2017.
[src:scot/africa] The .africa domain name registration was made available to the public in July 2017.
[src:scot/africa] The first large corporation to adopt the .africa domain was Absa.
[src:scot/africa] The .africa initiative is fully endorsed by the African Union Commission.
[src:scot/africa] According to Registry Africa, 78% of African governments support the TLD.
[src:scot/africa] The operator of the .africa gTLD is Registry Africa.
[src:scot/africa] Sponsoring Organisation is the ZA Central Registry trading as Registry.Africa.
[src:scot/africa] As of December 2024, there were about 52,000 registered .africa domains from 70 accredited registrars globally.
[src:scot/africa] The .africa application that was submitted by DotConnectAfrica Trust is the subject of an unresolved disagreement with ICANN (*DCA Trust v.
[src:scot/africa] ICANN*) following an Independent Review Panel (IRP) process that was invoked by DCA Trust under ICANN's accountability mechanism in October 2013.
[src:scot/africa] The IRP was administrated by the International Center for Dispute Resolution (ICDR) of the American Arbitration Association (AAA) New York, US.
[src:scot/africa] This had caused the non-completion of the evaluation of DCA Trust's application, which then led DCA Trust to challenge the ICANN Board decision through a series of accountability mechanism.
[src:scot/africa] As a result of the IRP declaration, the ICANN Board resolved on July 16, 2015, to reinstate DCA's application back to the new gTLD Process to complete initial evaluation.
[src:scot/africa] The IRP ruling also ordered ICANN to continue to refrain from delegating the .AFRICA gTLD to ZA Central Registry (ZACR).
[src:scot/africa] On January 20, 2016 ICANN was taken to the US Court regarding the way ICANN processed the IRP which declared DCA Trust the prevailing party in July 2015.
[src:scot/africa] The United States District Court, Central District of California in a ruling granted DCA Trust an Interim Relief for DotConnectAfrica and ordered ICANN to hold the delegation the .AFRICA top-level domain to ZACR.
[src:scot/africa] The same court also granted a Preliminary Injunction for DotConnectAfrica on April 12, 2016.
[src:scot/africa] ICANN and ZACR both contested the ruling; the court dismissed ZACR from the case leading to the filing of an interlocutory appeal.
[src:scot/africa] Six months later, the case was moved to the Superior Court of California owing to lack of jurisdiction.
[src:scot/africa] Superior Court Judge Howard Halm denied the motion by Dot Connect Africa to obtain an injunction that saw the launch of the top level domain at the African Union Commission, in Addis Ababa.
[src:scot/africa] The final delegation of the .africa Top Level Domain went to Registry Africa Ltd, a wholly owned subsidiary of the ZACR.
[src:scot/ai] It is a popular domain hack with companies and projects related to the artificial intelligence industry (AI).
[src:scot/ai] In 2021, Google Search analyst Gary Illyes announced that ".ai" had been added to Google’s list of generic country-code top-level domains, meaning that Google would no longer infer Anguilla-specific targeting from the ccTLD.
[src:scot/ai] Identity Digital began managing the domain as of January 2025.
[src:scot/ai] Registrations within **off.ai**, **com.ai**, **net.ai**, and **org.ai** are available worldwide without restriction.
[src:scot/ai] From 15 September 2009, second level registrations within **.ai** are available to everyone worldwide.
[src:scot/ai] The minimum registration term allowed for .ai domains is 2 through 10 years for registration and renewal, and a 2-year renewal for domain transfer.
[src:scot/ai] Identity Digital is the authority in charge of managing this extension.
[src:scot/ai] Registrations began on 16 February 1995.
[src:scot/ai] The limits on the number of characters used for the domain name are, at a minimum, from 1 to 3, depending on the registrar, and always at most 63 characters.
[src:scot/ai] The character set supported for .ai domain names includes A–Z, a–z, 0–9, and hyphen.
[src:scot/ai] As of November 2022, .ai domains cannot accommodate IDN characters.
[src:scot/ai] There are no requirements for registering a domain, including local and foreign residents.
[src:scot/ai] A .ai domain can be suspended or revoked, if the domain is involved in illegal activity such as violating trademarks or copyrights.
[src:scot/ai] Usage must not violate the laws of Anguilla.
[src:scot/ai] Filing a UDRP challenge requires using one of the ICANN Approved Dispute Resolution Service Providers.
[src:scot/ai] If the domain is with an ICANN accredited registrar, they should work with the arbitrator.
[src:scot/ai] Usually this means either doing nothing or transferring a domain. .ai domains are transferable to any desired registrars as the registration of domain is done maintaining EPP.
[src:scot/ai] There used to be a whois.ai-based platform of expired domains in which those could be procured and auctioned every ten days through a standard online process.
[src:scot/ai] The last auctions of such kind closed there in December 2024; the platform had been scheduled for shutdown on 30 June 2025, but remained online in the months following that date.
[src:scot/ai] Domains cost depends on the registrar, with yearly fees ranging from US$140 (the base fee, as established by Anguilla) to $200.
[src:scot/ai] As of July 2025, the highest-valued .ai domain is an undisclosed one sold on 8 November 2023, on Escrow.com, for US$1,500,000—months after an initial $300,000 sale to the same buyer.
[src:scot/ai] Among the publicly disclosed ones, the most valued, *fin.ai*, was sold for $1,000,000 in March 2025.
[src:scot/ai] On 16 December 2017, the .ai registry started supporting the Extensible Provisioning Protocol (EPP) and migrated all of its domains onto an EPP system.
[src:scot/ai] Consequently, many registrars are allowed to sell .ai domains.
[src:scot/ai] Since that date, the .ai ccTLD has also been popular with artificial intelligence companies and organisations.
[src:scot/ai] Though such trends are primarily seen among new AI based companies or startups, many established AI and Tech companies preferred not to opt for .ai domains.
[src:scot/ai] For example, DeepMind has its domain retained at .com; Meta has redirected its facebook.ai domain to ai.meta.com.
[src:scot/ai] The registration fees earned from the .ai domains go to the treasury of the Government of Anguilla.
[src:scot/ai] As per a 2018 *New York Times* report, the total revenue generated out of selling .ai domains was $2.9 million.
[src:scot/ai] In 2023, Anguilla's government made about US$32 million from fees collected for registering .ai domains; that amounted to over 10% of gross domestic product for the territory.
[src:scot/ai] "In the years before the real breakthrough of AI, revenue from .ai domains made up less than 1% of our state income, by 2025 it will be around 47%," explained Jose Vanterpool, Minister of Infrastructure and Communications (MICUHITES), in an interview with BBC.
[src:scot/ai] The high 90% renewal rate of .ai domains and the 2025 renewal wave of domains registered in 2023 are driving another surge in state revenues, according to Domaintechnik.
[src:scot/alsace] This **list of Internet top-level domains** (**TLD**) contains top-level domains, which are those domains in the DNS root zone of the Domain Name System of the Internet.
[src:scot/alsace] A list of the top-level domains by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) is maintained at the Root Zone Database.
[src:scot/alsace] IANA also oversees the approval process for new proposed top-level domains for ICANN.
[src:scot/alsace] As of February 2026, the IANA root database includes 1593 TLDs.
[src:scot/alsace] This database also includes 156 that are not assigned (revoked or retired) and 11 test domains, all of which are not represented in IANA's TLD listing nor in the root.zone file (the file also includes one root domain).
[src:scot/alsace] Seven generic top-level domains were created early in the development of the Internet, prior to the creation of ICANN in 1998.
[src:scot/alsace] As of 20 May 2017, there were 255 country-code top-level domains, purely in the Latin alphabet, using two-character codes.
[src:scot/alsace] As of June 2022, the number was 316, with the addition of internationalized domains.
[src:scot/alsace] Internationalized domain names have been proposed for Japan and Libya.
[src:scot/alsace] There are currently over 530 generic Internet top-level domains that use common English words.
[src:scot/alsace] These are now found in a separate article.
[src:scot/alsace] All of these TLDs are internationalized domain names (IDN) and support second-level IDNs.
[src:scot/alsace] Delegated to UOL subsidiary UBN Internet.
[src:scot/alsace] ICANN/IANA has created some special-use domain names which are meant for technical purposes.
[src:scot/alsace] ICANN/IANA owns all of the special-use domain names.
[src:scot/alsace] Besides the TLDs managed (or at least tracked) by IANA or ICANN, other independent groups have created, or had attempted to create, their own TLDs with varying technical specifications, functions, and outcomes.
[src:scot/alsace] Within Microsoft Windows there are some special purpose domain names that partially conflict with publicly assigned ones.
[src:scot/alsace] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) has submitted several requests for comments on TLDs that could be used to represent local devices and services.
[src:scot/alsace] Blockchain-based domains are registered and exchanged using a public blockchain like Ethereum.
[src:scot/alsace] Oftentimes, these domains serve specific functions such as creating human-readable references to smart contract addresses used in DApps or personal wallet addresses.
[src:scot/alsace] In the case of alternative DNS roots, organizations or projects make use of the same mechanisms of the DNS but instead take on the role of ICANN in managing and administering an entirely separate root zone, thus having the ability to create new TLDs independently.
[src:scot/alsace] However, this doesn't make these domains any less isolated from the rest of the internet, as the ability for clients to resolve them theoretically only requires switching to a recursive DNS resolver that recognizes and serves records underneath the alternate root zone.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] The domain names **.ngo** and **.ong** are generic top-level domains (gTLD) of the Domain Name System (DNS) used in the Internet, sponsored and managed by the Public Interest Registry.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] The .ngo domain name is an acronym which stands for "non-governmental organization", reflecting the intended usage of the domain.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] In June 2011, ICANN expanded the Internet's naming system to allow applications for new top-level domain names.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] The Public Interest Registry declared publicly an interest in the .ngo domain in August 2011 and applied for it in May 2012.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] The PIR simultaneously applied for the top-level domain .ong, which is a similarly recognisable initialism for "organisation non gouvernementale" in French, and equivalent terms in many other Romance languages such as Spanish, Portuguese, Italian and Romanian.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] Unlike the more prevalent .org domain, which is also managed by the Public Interest Registry, .ngo will require validation of the registrant's non-governmental status.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] Non-governmental organizations told the Public Interest Registry they needed a closed domain that validated the legitimacy of websites accepting online donations to avoid fraud.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] The Public Interest Registry plans to use the funds from selling .ngo domains to develop an "NGO Community Program" to reach out to NGOs in developing nations.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] It also intends to create a directory service of NGOs to support their SEO and visibility, and develop a closed community for NGOs to learn from each other.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] The new domains have been publicly available since May 6, 2015.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] Originally, registrants did not purchase an .ngo or .ong domain name separately, and a single registration was valid for two domain names which end in either .ngo or .ong but were otherwise identical.
[src:scot/ngo-and-ong] This policy was relaxed in June 2022, and .ngo and .ong domain names can now be purchased independently of each other.
[src:scot/scot] Originally, *.sco* was proposed in a campaign.
[src:scot/scot] In 2008 dotCYMRU, dotEUS, dotSCOT and dotBZH formed ECLID.
[src:scot/scot] Later it was decided to allow newly proposed top-level domains for introduction some time in 2013, and a list of applications for these was published in June 2012; the domain .scot was included.
[src:scot/scot] On 27 January 2014, dotScot Registry, a not-for-profit organisation established in 2009, announced that it had agreed terms to operate the .scot domain name, with plans to get it up and running later in summer of 2014.
[src:scot/scot] On 15 July 2014, .scot was officially launched.
[src:scot/scot] The first .scot domain name to go live was calico.scot, registered by hosting company Calico Internet Ltd.
[src:scot/scot] On 17 February 2015, the Scottish Government migrated its website from Scotland.gov.uk to gov.scot.
[src:scot/scot] Likewise, the Scottish Parliament moved from Scottish.parliament.uk to parliament.scot in May 2016, to coincide with the 2016 elections.
[src:scot/scot] The 2017 Global Amendment to the base New GeoTLD Registry Agreement is effective as of 31 July 2017.
[src:scot/scot] On 3 May 2018 the dotScot Registry lifted registration restrictions on locality domains (based on towns, etc.) and other premium names.
